          <h3>Why is this website called The Noneo?</h3>
          <p>
            <strong>The Noneo</strong> is the Korean literal translation of the original Chinese character name of the Analects, which is Lunyu (論語). The two Chinese characters are transcribed as such:
          </p>
          <p class="lead">
            English: The Analects of Confucius
          </p>
          <p class="lead">
            Traditional Chinese: 論語 lúnyǔ
          </p>
          <p class="lead">
            Korean: 논어 noneo <small>(pronounced as /noʊn ə/ or 'non-uh')</small>
          </p>
          <p>
            While the most commonly cited translation in English of 論語/논어 is <i>'Edited Conversations'</i>, the 論/논 character can be translated as 'Discuss/Debate' and the 語/어 character translated as 'Conversation'. <a href="#c-9" class="citation" title="Ancient Chinese characters are difficult to translate, because their meanings are more symbollic than semantic. For example, the original character for 'filial piety' (孝) is of the 'son' character (子) written beneath the 'senior' (耂) chracter to signify that the son is literally 'supporting' the senior."><span id="rfn-9"></span>[9]</a><a href="#c-10" class="citation" title="Observant readers will notice that there is a 1 to 1 translation from the Ancient Chinese characters to Korean characters going on here. This is true for most Ancient Chinese characters."><span id="rfn-10"></span>[10]</a>  The actual literal translations are more accurately <i>'Discussed Conversations'</i>. The <i>'Edited Conversations'</i> translation comes from the effort to more accurately describe the fact that Confucius' disciples edited the conversations they had and compiled it into a literary work, as most modern scholars agree that Confucius is not the author of the Analects in the traditional sense of the word. It is comparable to how Socrates never wrote down any of his ideas either, but he is cited for his philosophies as recorded by his disciple, Plato.
          </p>
          <p>
            While I am familiar with the reading of the Chinese characters, the language I am most familiar with the Analects is in Korean. I have learned about Confucius and his ethics in the Korean language, and have spent the most time observing them in the South Korean culture.
          </p>
          <p>
            From this point on, I will use the term 'Noneo' when I am referring to this website and its interpretations, and use the term 'Analects' when I am referring to the original text. It is to differentiate from the many more traditional and popular interpretations that exist of the Analects, as I am more of a philosopher and synthesizer rather than a researcher or historian.
          </p>
